# RFC-0008

# Distributed Attestation Network (DAN)

Status: Draft

Version: 0.1

Depends on:

* RFC-0000 Core Object Model

---

# 1. Purpose

The Distributed Attestation Network (DAN) defines how the AiDN network objectively evaluates publicly available Endpoints.

Validation SHALL be decentralized.

No central authority determines trust.

Trust emerges from publicly verifiable attestations.

---

# 2. Objectives

The DAN SHALL:

* continuously evaluate public Endpoints;
* reward independent Validators;
* prevent self-certification;
* produce publicly verifiable observations;
* enable every participant to calculate their own trust scores.

---

# 3. Core Principles

### DAN-1

Validators never certify themselves.

---

### DAN-2

Validators never choose which Endpoint they validate.

---

### DAN-3

Validation results are public.

---

### DAN-4

Every participant independently computes trust from published attestations.

---

# 4. Hypervisor Reputation

Hypervisor reputation consists of two independent components.

```text
Hypervisor Reputation

=

Infrastructure Reputation (50%)

+

Endpoint Reputation (50%)
```

---

## 4.1 Infrastructure Reputation (50%)

Infrastructure Reputation reflects the quality of Hypervisor operation.

Examples include:

* uptime;
* availability;
* protocol compliance;
* successful request execution;
* network participation;
* advertisement consistency;
* heartbeat stability.

Changes affecting Hypervisor configuration SHALL reduce Infrastructure Reputation proportionally.

The reduction SHALL be temporary and recover through subsequent successful observations.

---

## 4.2 Endpoint Reputation (50%)

The remaining reputation is distributed equally across all validated Endpoints published by the Hypervisor.

Example:

```text
50%

↓

4 Endpoints

↓

12.5% each
```

Adding, removing or modifying an Endpoint SHALL proportionally redistribute the Endpoint Reputation.

Only the affected Endpoint(s) require re-validation.

Existing validated Endpoints retain their accumulated reputation.

---

# 5. Validator Pool

Validators form an ordered Validator Pool.

Validators MAY join the pool after satisfying network requirements.

Example requirements:

* minimum Hypervisor Reputation;
* validated Validator Endpoint;
* stable operational history;
* protocol compliance.

New Validators SHALL be appended to the end of the pool.

The Validator Pool SHALL operate using FIFO rotation.

---

# 6. Validation Pool

The network maintains a Validation Pool containing all public Endpoints eligible for validation.

Private Endpoints SHALL NOT appear in the Validation Pool.

Endpoints MAY opt out of validation while remaining publicly accessible.

Opt-out Endpoints SHALL NOT receive validation-based reputation.

---

# 7. Epoch

Validation operates in discrete Epochs.

At the beginning of each Epoch:

1. The first N Validators are selected from the Validator Pool.
2. Each selected Validator receives responsibility for another Validator's assignment.
3. No Validator selects its own validation targets.
4. Validator assignments SHALL be deterministic and verifiable.

---

# 8. Endpoint Selection

Assigned Validators select Endpoints probabilistically.

Selection probability SHOULD increase according to factors including:

* newly published Endpoint;
* recently modified ConfigurationHash;
* low observation count;
* low confidence score;
* time since previous validation.

Endpoint operators SHALL NOT know in advance which Epoch will validate their Endpoint.

---

# 9. Validation Execution

Validators SHALL submit normal execution requests.

Validation traffic SHALL be indistinguishable from ordinary client traffic.

The validated Endpoint SHALL receive normal compensation for every validation request.

Validators SHALL receive Epoch rewards rather than payments from Endpoint operators.

---

# 10. Validator Rewards

Validator rewards originate from Epoch emission.

Rewards SHALL NOT depend on the number of validation requests submitted.

This prevents Validators from generating excessive validation traffic for profit.

---

# 11. Published Attestation

Every validation SHALL produce a signed Attestation.

The Attestation SHALL include at minimum:

* Validator ID;
* Endpoint ID;
* BundleHash;
* ConfigurationHash;
* Model Class;
* Capability;
* Validation Specification;
* timestamp;
* test identifier;
* measured observations;
* Validator signature.

Attestations SHALL be immutable.

---

# 12. ConfigurationHash

Every execution-relevant Endpoint modification SHALL generate a new ConfigurationHash.

ConfigurationHash SHALL be included in every Attestation.

Changing ConfigurationHash invalidates future trust accumulation until new attestations are collected.

Historical attestations remain valid for their associated ConfigurationHash.

---

# 13. Endpoint Scope

Validation applies to Endpoints, not entire Hypervisors.

Hypervisors MAY publish multiple independent Endpoints.

Each Endpoint accumulates validation independently.

---

# 14. Validator Competency

A Validator SHALL possess an Endpoint capable of evaluating the Capability being validated.

Examples:

* LLM Validators validate LLM Endpoints.
* TTS Validators generate text prompts and evaluate synthesized audio.
* STT Validators generate audio samples and evaluate transcribed text.
* Image Validators generate prompts and evaluate produced images.

Validators SHALL perform approximate quality assessment using observable characteristics.

---

# 15. Validator Qualification

A Validator Endpoint SHALL itself be successfully validated before participating in the Validator Pool.

Validators SHALL continuously maintain sufficient competence.

Validators whose competence falls below required thresholds SHALL be suspended from the Validator Pool.

---

# 16. Model Class Compatibility

Validators SHALL validate only Model Classes for which they possess sufficient capability.

A Validator Endpoint SHALL be approximately equivalent to or stronger than the validated Model Class.

Validator Competency Profiles define acceptable validation relationships.

---

# 17. Reference Test Suites

Validation SHALL primarily rely on publicly available benchmark suites.

Examples include:

* MMLU;
* HumanEval;
* MBPP;
* GSM8K;
* LiveCodeBench;
* MMMU;
* domain-specific capability benchmarks.

Validation Specifications determine which benchmark subsets are applicable to each Model Class.

---

# 18. Trust Computation

The network publishes observations.

The network does not publish trust.

Every participant computes trust independently using:

* published Attestations;
* Validator history;
* ConfigurationHash history;
* personal trust policies.

---

# 19. Design Invariants

Invariant 1

Validators never validate themselves.

---

Invariant 2

Validators never choose their own validation targets.

---

Invariant 3

Validation traffic is indistinguishable from production traffic.

---

Invariant 4

Attestations are public and immutable.

---

Invariant 5

Trust is locally computed.

---

Invariant 6

Configuration changes reduce reputation proportionally and require renewed validation.

---

Invariant 7

Validation applies to Endpoints.

Infrastructure reputation applies to Hypervisors.
